Comment:
And yet they're still lazy as hell with their research and design.  The setting for this movie is just an ignorant, childish mishmash of several quite different and diverse cultures that only have coincidental geographical proximity in common.  They even hired a Vietnamese actor to play the lead, and Vietnam is part of the Sinosphere, which means heavily influenced by China, and for that matter the movie is, too, along with the rest of East Asia.  Isn't this supposed to be about Southeast Asia, whatever that's supposed to mean?  Do Disney seriously believe that all Asians are the same?   This is just another cynical example of cultural ignorance and appropriation by Disney just to fill their pockets with cash.  Why aren't leftists screaming for this movie's cancellation?  I'm no leftist, and even I find this offensive.  They're too lazy with their research, and can't even design a freaking dragon that doesn't look like Elsa!  What a joke!

Disney are a bunch of leftists who practice intolerant "cancel culture" on their own actors, so they should do us all a favor and cancel this embarrassment of an animated feature, and then cancel themselves because they have nothing to do with Walt Disney except to shame his name.

¬†@SomeoneCommenting¬†  And they ripped themselves off to start with--absolutely zero originality whatsoever.  Let them know we don't approve by not paying a penny for this movie.  That's the only thing that counts and would have any effect whatsoever.  Watch the movie later anyway, if you must, on Disney+.  Just don't pay all that money merely to see it slightly earlier.  Their clear lack of effort and care is not worth paying anything for.

Better yet, don't watch it at all (no one watching at all sends an even stronger message) or cancel Disney+ altogether.  Do what you can to stand up for yourself and the money you spend as a consumer.  They shouldn't own us, they need us, and we should be more discerning and demand better of them.  We have the ability and power--all we need is the will, and frankly this latest effort of theirs looks pathetically derivative and weak, in addition to offensive in how it treats Asians like we're all Chinese (plus a clumsy, random mix of stuff from Southeast Asia to exploit that market).  No offense meant to the Chinese by me, but Disney's obvious pandering to them and that big, lucrative market even offends those folks, so why shouldn't it especially offend other Asians and anyone else who tends to get offended by anyone's ignorant, clumsy, lazy attempts to "honor" other cultures with their cynical, money-grubbing schemes?

Comment: ¬†@dewolf123¬† What is that bad standard of modern Disney? I don't really get it. I prefer Pixar over Disney, yes, but I don't see anything wrong in Disney movies. Even those live action remake titles. I mean, I criticized problems in Lion King, but it wasn't super bad movie. Just missed the point of the TLK. But Mulan for example was ingenious. Contrary to what most of people say, I enjoyed it very much. Right now my top 2 fav Disney movies are Mulan... and Mulan. And even though I was afraid they ruin everything I loved in original Mulan (and they did!), the new version was extraordinary for me anyway. Just very different. I can agree that they could have tried too hard with the the threat, adding too much magic, but well, original Mulan had magic too. Not on that scale, but they both shown the similar problems. And the live action version was even more mature with the problem. Original Mulan was child story. It had shown that women were treated differently, but it wasn't the main point. The story in new Mulan emphasized this problem to the bigger scale. Even Mushu, which is my fav Mulan character was non-existent there and I didn't see the problem. Comment:
It looks like just an ignorant, childish mishmash of several quite different and diverse cultures that only have coincidental geographical proximity in common.  They even hired a Vietnamese actor to play the lead, and Vietnam is part of the Sinosphere, which means heavily influenced by China, and for that matter the movie is, too, along with the rest of East Asia.  Isn't this supposed to be about Southeast Asia, whatever that's supposed to mean?  Do Disney seriously believe that all Asians are the same?   This is just another cynical example of cultural ignorance and appropriation by Disney just to fill their pockets with cash.  Why aren't leftists screaming for this movie's cancellation?  I'm no leftist, and even I find this offensive.  They're too lazy with their research, and can't even design a freaking dragon that doesn't look like Elsa!  What a joke!

Disney are a bunch of leftists who practice intolerant "cancel culture" on their own actors, so they should do us all a favor and cancel this embarrassment of an animated feature, and then cancel themselves because they have nothing to do with Walt Disney.

Comment: I hesitated to watch this movie for soooo long because my expectations for Disney are low. I'm over all of the musicals. But man  my husband and I decided to put it on after another father recommended it to us. So we watched it with our daughter and man.... It blew my expectations out of the water. Thank you soooo much for not making it a musical. I went and looked up the work they put into this and the director (his debut film) purposely didn't make it a musical because he wanted a contemporary film. The filmmakers that made it based the culture of the movie off of multiple cultures from Southeast Asia. They visited the Philippines, Thailand, Indonesia, Cambodia, Laos, Singapore and Vietnam. I have to say it was very respectable. If you, like me, are sick of Disney musicals, then you'll find this one a breath of fresh air.

Comment: It's interesting that you say that because a whole new team worked the live action Mulan whereas the studio that is making Raya is made by the same (albeit an evolved version of the same) studio. Walt taught the 9 old men who taught up through much of the renaissance who taught up through today. It's a legacy preserving thing that ensures films which come from the Animation studio itself are able to stand cohesively with its predecessors. So it seems to me that the charm never really left. I'll edit my comment if the replies get bad enough;

-I don't care about it hurting a culture's feelings or something, I would rather it be accurate to the culture so I can understand it better personally, as well as others. -I really like learning.

Comment: Eric Spearman I think the difference is Aladdin wasn‚Äôt trying to be the animation equivalent of an action oriented summer blockbuster. It was a quirky musical with some action scenes thrown in here and there. This movie seems to be trying to set up some strong world building rules and the joke doesn‚Äôt land because it feels out of place. The dragon is clearly going to be used a comedic relief, but is poised in the position of being the second protagonist and crux of the story. The genie was in most moments a plot device so he was more free to be comedic fluff. But it seems like the dragon might have her own arc and will play a more pivotal role, so she needs to be more grounded in reality and time. That being said, the time period they are going for would not have group projects and grades like traditional modern schools. It breaks the internal logic and therefore undermines the story by breaking you out of it.

Comment:
¬†@loveyourself3364¬† If in a linguistic standpoint, philippine languages and malay both belong to the austronesian language group.
Now in terms of genetics, not so much but they do share austronesian ancestors.
In short, Indonesia and Malaysia were first inhabited by austroasiatic people then these people mixed with austronesian speakers from the Philippines. These austronesian speakers also came from southern china then taiwan then the Philippines. Genetics of people from western indonesia as well as malaysia are dominated by this austroasiatic component whereas those coming from eastern part (except the papuans) have more austronesian component. Studies also showed that proto-malay have a lot of austroasiatic component compared to austronesian. This is why western indonesians and malaysians are more closely related to southern thais and cambodians than they are to modern filipinos. Filipinos on the other hand are more closely related to gaoshan/ami taiwanese groups and probably some other southern chinese ethnic group than they are to indonesians or malaysians.

Comment: @EivŒ∏r Raven Clan you're not wrong in that assumption, and yes Disney has used the same format for quite a while now. However, Raya stands out a LOT more. She was willing to beat up a child, and she doesn't just "find" something, her father simply inspired her to become an advocate of peace. The dragon's imo is simply symbolic, and a bad guy doesn't simply "show up", these guys have been fighting amongst each other for centuries, all trying to gain control of the dragon so that they would wield the most political power. It's exactly like the situation between China and the US, where the US strongly advocates for Hong Kong's independence while China repeatedly claims it as their own. Hong Kong isn't worth too much to China, they're economy is already growing faster than the US's, but it's the political symbolism that the Chinese are trying to get out of it. That is exactly what is happening in Raya, and I really like it.

Comment:
¬†@ssjsmith8879¬† southeast Asia does not mean China. China isn‚Äôt even in Southeast Asia, it‚Äôs in east Asia, there‚Äôs a difference (unless you never took world geography classes). In addition, an interview from the producer of the film, Osnat, reveals that before COVID they went to Cambodia, Laos, Vietnam, Indonesia, Thailand, Malaysia, and Singapore to gain cultural knowledge of these indigenous countries. The animated fighting styles can also be seen to be drawn from Pencak Silat, Muoy Thai, and Arnis, which all come from Southeast Asia. No I am not making those words up. Pencak Silat originated from Indonesia, Muy Thai is a Thailand based boxing style martial arts, and Arnis is the national martial arts of the Philippines. Not once was China even mentioned. In addition, the concept of dragons are not exclusively Chinese. Japan, Korea, Vietnam, and Thailand all have dragons as well. 

The fact that your assumptions claim that all of these concepts and made up nations in an animated film suited for younger audiences came from China is either a pure lack of cultural knowledge of Asia as a whole, or a belief of exaggerated stigma against Asians. Comment:
¬†@ssjsmith8879¬† Your first argument of questioning my validity judging off of the number of subscribers and content can easily be nullified by fact checking me. Simply googling everything that I said, and you will find that I spoke nothing but the truth from articles that I found. Your second argument is claiming that the art style and recent history of Disney has revolved around China. That, unfortunately, is false. The live action Mulan, though cringe in many parts, was undoubtedly based off China. However, Star Wars is not based off China, it‚Äôs based off a struggle in a futuristic galaxy as an unseen energy called ‚Äúthe force‚Äù manipulates the galaxy in war in attempt to achieve perfect balance. The only main screen actor/actress that is related to Asia was Kelly Marie Tran, who played Rose. For your information, she was actually born in San Diego, California, and her parents were immigrants from VIETNAM. In addition, if we are to list every single TV show and movie created by Disney after 2018 (when the production of Mulan live action began), we can a long list of The Mandalorian, Marvel Hero Project, Lady and the Tramp (2019), Artemis Fowl, Soul, Black is King, Togo, WandaVision, Becoming, and so much more that I don‚Äôt feel like listing. In addition to that, the conical hat is not specifically limited to China. In fact, the conical hat can be seen used in many Asian countries such as Bangladesh, Bhutan, Cambodia, Indonesia, Japan, Korea, Laos, and much more countries. On a side note, avatar and the last air bender is not owned by Disney, it is owned by Nickelodeon, which is owned by Viacom International, which is not owned by Walt Disney studios and is a competitor of Disney.

You are entitled to your taste of shows and what you like. However, you are not entitled to the uninformed opinion of believing that everything Disney is doing is based off China. No one is entitled to be ignorant.

Let me just quote from this article: https://comicbook.com/movies/news/raya-and-the-last-dragon-sisu-baymax-connection/

"Specifically I would also add that the character of Sisu was a very specific attempt at, you know, portraying something that is deeply rooted in Southeast Asian mythology, which is that of the NƒÅga, which is that a dragon, but a very specific dragon and a deep deep connection with that dragon with water, which to us made it fresh and interesting in a world that's had many dragons depicted on screen," Hall said. "We feel like we found a, you know, not unlike you know Baymax. It felt similar in that like 'oh my god we've got, how many robots have we seen in the movies? What are we gonna do something different, what are we gonna do?' And then in the research found inflatable robots being researched at Carnegie Mellon and Sisu is sort of the same thing. It's like, obviously we wanted a dragon in the film but it was a unique take on a dragon, and again, going into the research, looking at the cultures that we're profiling, we found a very unique take on the dragon so it allowed us some really cool... it's hard to talk about without spoiling, but there's a very deep connection between Sisu and water that is really, really beautiful stuff on screen."

Comment:
¬†@frankpetersen6624¬† Lesson #1 - Geography
South-east Asia: Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar, Malaysia, Thailand, Vietnam, Brunei, East Timor, Indonesia, Philippines, Singapore
South Asia: India, Sri Lanka, Bhutan, Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Afghanistan
*Technically, there are places in India that can be considered as a part of Maritime South-east Asia geographically.
Note: Maybe you'll find a few similarities in the South Asian cultures (the Indian subcontinent was divided to form different nations - i'm sure you're aware of British colonization) but I can assure you that all of these countries have very DIFFERENT cultures. 
Lesson #2 - GK
Native Indians (USA) are very different from Indians (India). 
So if someone asks you to refer to them as Native Americans/Native Indians, it's probably because they are that & not the Indians that you're thinking of. So to answer your question - No, You are wrong, Native Americans are not Indians.
Lesson #3 - Social Studies
The term 'Black' belongs to the category of race which is different from ethnicity or nationality. Thus, a 'Black' person might be African American or Jamaican or Haitian or Nigerian BUT the term 'Indian' does not represent a race. It specifically refers to the people who belong to the country India or are people of Indian birth/descent/origin. So, if we go by your example (you said that you don't mind being called White/you're Italian), calling someone Indian when they actually belong to some other South-east Asian country (let's say Malaysia) would be the equivalent of calling you German just because you look white. So, I think you now understand why it is actually better to call someone South Asian or Asian instead of Indian because you won't be assuming their nationality/ethnicity, just like calling you White is better than assuming your nationality/ethnicity and calling you German when you're actually Italian.
Lesson #4 - Disney & your assumptions
Now, let's get down to what started all of this...So, yes, Disney did start off as an American corporation. It made movies about stories that primarily belonged to the Western world but with time, it became an international entertainment conglomerate that now have numerous studios working under it. Now ofcourse, if their audience went from a part of the world to the whole world, it is fairly obvious that the same thing would happen to their stories. You can't be serving the same "White" characters everytime and expect people all over the world to continuously enjoy it and the thing is, why would you even want to limit your stories to certain attributes in a world where half the things are fictional? 
And yes, although you think that there are numerous Indian Disney movies out there, I would like to clarify and tell you that out of all the names you took, only The Jungle Book is set in India. None of the other come close to the Indian culture. Although, you think this movie (Raya and the Last Dragon) is set in India or has got anything to do with India, that's far from the truth. None of the characters or places resemble anything you'd find in India. 
Fun Fact: This film is set in a fictional fantasy land called Kumandra, inspired by Southeast Asian cultures from Laos, Thailand, Cambodia, Vietnam, Myanmar, Malaysia, Indonesia, and the Philippines.
All I understand is that you want an Italian Disney movie or any other movie with 'White' characters but all I can say is that you're highly mistaken if you think they're making these movies to appease a certain community because honestly there are a very few movies compared to the number of different cultures you'll find here and you know what, we're okay with that. It's enough knowing that they're trying to make great movies while trying to represent people that do not look the same because there's a world beyond it. Soul was probably the first movie with enough Black people to actually represent the population & when that is the case when Black people belong to the same country, just imagine how it's even fair to think that all the people belonging to the Eastern countries (very wide term) are getting proper representation...It's okay to want a movie with Italian or White (honestly I wouldn't have used the term 'White' these many times but it seems that you're comfortable with it so this is the only way to explain) characters...Hell, I'd enjoy watching Italian characters too! But your demand/expectation of wanting only that and thinking that the few movies that actually have people belonging to different cultures are a few too many, is what is unreasonable and the reason why everyone in this comment section is upset at you. I went through some of your comments & everything that I've written here is my attempt to genuinely educate you regarding these matters. It doesn't matter if you're 43, I'm giving you the benefit of doubt and hope that you actually understand the difference. Thankyou.

It‚Äôs similar because Avatar is based on a lot of Asian culture, history, and mythology, mostly East Asian (China, Japan, Korea) with a few others thrown in (Tibet, Mainland Southeast Asia, and Inuit). Avatar and incarnation is a Buddhist/Hindu thing so I‚Äôd say it‚Äôs Indian as well.

Comment: Laotian here and the representation of the SEA dishes is a favorite element of mine in this film. Beautifully researched. Durian, Longan, Jackfruit, Congee, and the main dish to bring in the unity... GLORIOUS Tom Yum. I vaguely know that there has been a history of Thailand and Laos being at odds even though we are so similar. They made this film so well and I'm very proud of the team who worked on it and grateful to have a film like this. Other things to know about: the armadillo-like creature name "Tuk Tuk" is what we call taxis. The con baby's name "Noi" means little one or young girl. Something personal, Raya's dad reminds me of mine in looks and soul. Boun is a favorite, reminds me of little cousins. All the characters remind me of someone I know in real life. Synchronic. Best Disney film. Thank you.

Comment:
Dragons are not really a SEA thing. SEA dragons are more like serpents. They're more prominent in indochina, but not much elsewhere. For example, in the Malay archipelago, the "main" mythical creature is the garuda (thunderbird).

The reason the producers chose dragon is because it fits better with Western audiences expectations of the Far East. Also the look and feel of the production skews more East Asian. It doesn't really look like SE Asia. 

Still, to have a major production set in the region is progress, I guess. SEA is grossly underrepresented in comparison to EA.

Comment: Wonderful movie! One of our favorites!! I think if you are someone who does have some cultural background on the countries portrayed in this move then this is definitely so cool to watch!  I am Chinese and my fiancee is Philippino and Taiwanese. He does Muay Thai and has been to Thailand! We both love East Asian culture so this was a huge hit for us! He was especially excited for Tuk Tuk (he got ride in a real one). It's so refreshing to see another Asian inspired movie especially with not one but 2 strong female leads! It's amazing to see how many different east asian cultures they included in this as well, specifically the islands! I love Avatar and I love this too but I feel like Avatar is more about all of Asia and the plot is similar but I love the story behind this too. I know a lot of people are angry about the dragons design and the voice but remember this is a kids movie.. Also each culture has a different take on how dragons look... A lot of the cultures represented in this movie are Laos, Thailand, Philippines, Singapore, Malaysia, etc. Their dragons look much different than the typical Chinese dragons you normally see. I think the design is absolutely beautiful as well! I actually haven't bothered to watch a lot of the new Disney movie's but I'm SO happy I watched this one!

Comment: The prosperous land of Kumandra is ravaged by the Druun, evil spirits that turn people and dragons to stone. Comment:
People complain about the film teaching you to be too trusting of your abusers, but that's not it. The Fang tribe believed the gem was the sole source of prosperity for the Heart tribe, so they sought to steal it, which only caused the Druun to awaken and everything to descend into chaos. 

The Fang tribe believed the other tribes would blame them if they were to be revived, but perceptive Raya understood Namaari's fear of this scenario and attempted to prove to Namaari that she held no such grudge against her and only wanted to restore peace to Kumandra. Unfortunately, she let her fear overtake her at the last second and accidentally shot Sisu with her bow, enraging her and engaging in combat with Namaari before realizing protecting Citizens from the Drug was more important than being consumed by anger.

Comment:
The Lord of the Rings 6: Anna & The Magical Dragon


In the 3rd chapter of the Arendelle Saga, Anna (Kristen Bell), her son & their friends continue on their epic quest to destroy Lord Voldemort's one & only horcrux; the One Ring. But when they encounter more and more enemies in their path through a magical world paradise of Kumandra, where humans and dragons lived together in harmony long ago and an evil force threatened the land, the dragons sacrificed themselves to save humanity, 500 years later, that same evil has returned, they team up with a magical, mythical, self-deprecating dragon; Sisu (Awkwafina) & Raya (Kelly Marie Tran); a lone warrior whose wit is as sharp as her blade. Characters also include a street-savvy 10-year-old entrepreneur named Boun, the formidable giant Tong and a thieving toddler Noi with her band of Ongis. Together, they fight their way against the Druun & the borders of the land to find all of the dragon gem pieces.


Cast:
Kristen Bell, Awkwafina, Joseph May, Mandy Moore, Kelly Maire Tran, Rob Rackstraw, Zachary Levi, Elijah Wood, Daniel Radcliffe, Chris Pratt, Natalie Portman, Izaac Wang, Dakota Fanning, Kodi Smit-McPhee, Matt Wilkinson, Gemma Chan, Bret Iwan, Tony Anselmo, Benedict Wong, Sandra Oh, Thalia Tran, Alan Tudyk, Daniel Dae Kim, Chris Evans, Scarlett Johansson, Brie Larson, Paul Rudd, Gordon Ip, Dichen Lachman, Patti Harrison, Jon "Dumbfoundead" Park, Jona Xiao, Sung Kang, Sierra Katow, Lucille Soong, Ross Butler, Francois Chau, Paul Yen, Kerry Shale, Colm Feore, David Menkin, Keith Wickham, Christopher Ragland, Joe Mills, Nicola Stapleton, Steven Kynman, William Hope, Jules de Jongh, Glenn Wrage, Rasmus Hardiker, Jonathan Broadbent, Teresa Gallagher, Eddie Redmayne, Rufus Jones, Olivia Colman, Ben Small, Yvonne Grundy, Darren Boyd, Sophie Cloquhoun, Jim Howick, Colin McFarlane, Hugh Bonneville

¬†@marcuscheng9398¬† Evangelion, no. But AOT is really good. Not sure about Demon Slayer, saw the first episodes up until after his encounter with Michael Jackson and the weird house. It's not so much to talk about as everybody has already said it: Demon Slayer is a typical anime formula but does it really well.

And for Evangelion. Hard no for that symbolic shit. The entire premise is lacking, the urgency is gone cause you don't feel anything for the world and the entire damn plot is just there to promote symbolism. I feel more invested in the plot of Danganronpa with their constant jabbering about hope vs despair.

If I want a movie about characters I'd watch Lion King animated or Goodwill Hunting.

Comment: If you watch this movie and REALLY watch it, you'll find that it delivers a very irresponsible message of "Just trust and everything will be okay" which is wrong. That's not how trust works in the real world. It's supposed to be "know who to trust and who not to". In the real world, there will be people who are dead set on taking advantage of you, and you should never give them a single amount of your trust. Trust is earned, not given. The whole message is just extremely irresponsible but hey, maybe big companies like Disney want to teach kids to be gullible and naive. Makes it more convenient for them to profit over their audience. When I watched this film, I knew it was going to be centered around the concept of trust. I thought it was going to show that the audience of the consequences of being too trusting or being too mistrusting. But no, this movie blatantly pushes the "just trust and the world won't be broken" agenda. The agenda is even inscribed in the song. "When you just trust." What I find disturbing is the extreme amount of support and praise this movie gets and the only a few people who reviewed it were the ones to all agree that it delivers a toxic message. Reality check, just cause it's a Disney movie, doesn't mean its message is correct. No amount of visuals, soundtrack, and flashy cgi can change the fact that it has a bad, irresponsible message. Don't trust this film. Don't trust Disney. I can't believe we're teaching our kids to be this gullible and naive now. But I guess big companies like Disney want that, don't they? Makes it more convenient for them to keep on profiting from a gullible population.

Comment:
Rating: 6/10
Review: 
Raya's friends and father are more likeable than her. Raya is pretty and I know that her character has potential but I just didn't think that they developed her character well. I tried to like her but I felt so conflicted with her character. My favorite though, is definitely tuk tuk and sisu. It's funny cause when I first saw the trailer, I thought that sisu was going to that be annoying character, but I ended up liking her lol. Now, namaari and virana on other hand, I'm not convinced with their redemption arc, they were forgivin too easily. If they want to redeem these two antagonist, they could've done more to justify their redemption. 

Anyway, the concept of this movie is about trust but I think they could've done better with the delivery because I honesty think it was done pretty poorly. Like Raya, it has potential to be good, but they did not do a good job expressing that concept by making a 'meh' storyline. In the storyline, there's hardly any hard challenge or conflict that I feel like everything happen so fast which is dissapointing. At the end, I did not learned anything significant. I honestly just wish they made a better storyline for this movie. I like the animation though, it was so realistic and smooth, it was good.

Comment:
While having a great message to pass down its audience the movie is mediocre at best.

The environments feel empty and lifeless. You can argue that it's a world where most people are turned into stone and lifelessness is something that needs to be huge part of it. But in the end when I see markets, docks and places inside populated areas with extremely little going on both in terms of living beings and objects all I can think of is they just cut down the budget. Even the chase through the docks and market with the (more on that later) baby and monkeys felt weird. Everything is too tidy and this lack of chaos means that either they didn't have the skill (new animators) or budget to do better. Even the great outdoors lacks any life. You literally cannot see a single firefly, cricket or butterfly. Throughout the whole movie I think there are 3-4 times of a single representative of the wild life on the screen.

The music is also something that struck me as lackluster. You have this cool traditional music. But then you get some hip-hop (?) and techno mix and at the weirdest moments on top of that. Sometimes the music actually took me out of the moment. This is probably the first Disney movie where I was utterly disappointed by the soundtrack. And for some reason Disney decided to remove any sort of singing, dancing or some sort of musical act.

The characters are not really that great either both in terms of animation and in terms of personality and overall presence on the screen. The baby in particular was creepy most of the time. It was adorable when...well...it was being a baby. But in the many instances when it was trying to behave like a grownup it had a weird expression that freaked me out. I think most of the budget for the characters went into the fighting animations, which are indeed very impressive. There is too much emphasis on realistic motion but it is a known fact that animation is not only about that.

There are many other things (plot, environmental effects etc.) that I can talk about but the points I've listed above are - in my opinion - enough.

Sadly I cannot recommend this movie. Of course this is just my personal 30+ year old dude's opinion. :D

Comment:
I hate this trailer. So many fucking spoilers:
-dad (or whoever he is) dies, because of course he does.
-ruins all mystery around the dragon's appearance. Its silhouette looks fearsome, why would you spoil the fact that it's a female version of Toothless?
-spoils the fact that not only can she shape-shift, but she can shape-shift into a human, and here's exactly what it looks like.
-a badass movie with moments of levity is great over the course of 2hrs. Going from deadly serious to goofy dragon in 2 minutes makes it seem like just another obnoxiously-dumb kids movie.
-the baby thing just makes the above point worse. While it may work in the movie, it makes the trailer look like 2000's internet "i'M lYkE, sOoOo RaNdOm, ROFLCOPTERSSS!!!1"-tier humor
-A trailer like this needs to be all badassery, then flash the title card, THEN switch to something funny for one sec, then flip to the "coming to theaters on _____" screen. That is how you make shit like the baby work, but her pet rolly-polly animal would have worked way better. The baby is weird as fuck and super offputting in this context. Like the dragon's appearance, it should have been left out of the trailer entirely and saved as a funny surprise.
